aThere has been modeling on entire seasons, shortened seasons and everyone right now is interested in playing that full season any way possible,a said Virginia Tech athletic director Whit Babcock. aBut we realize that could change.a
Virginia Tech athletic director Whit Babcock (at left, shown with menas basketball coach Mike Young) said on a teleconference Wednesday that he does not doubt revenue will be down in the 2020-21 school year. But he isnat sure how big the drop might be.
Virginia Tech spring-sports seniors, such as softball player Olivia Lattin, have been given another year of eligibility. If all current spring seniors returned at their current scholarship amounts, it would cost Tech $668,000.

aThere has been modeling on entire seasons, shortened seasons and everyone right now is interested in playing that full season any way possible,a said Virginia Tech athletic director Whit Babcock. aBut we realize that could change.a
Virginia Tech athletic director Whit Babcock (at left, shown with menas basketball coach Mike Young) said on a teleconference Wednesday that he does not doubt revenue will be down in the 2020-21 school year. But he isnat sure how big the drop might be.
Virginia Tech spring-sports seniors, such as softball player Olivia Lattin, have been given another year of eligibility. If all current spring seniors returned at their current scholarship amounts, it would cost Tech $668,000.
Virginia Tech spring sports seniors, such as baseball player Tanner Thomas, have been given another year of eligibility. If all Tech spring seniors returned at their current scholarship amounts, it would cost Tech $668,000.
Virginia Tech spring-sports seniors, such as women's lacrosse player Taylor Caskey, have been given another year of eligibility. If all current spring seniors returned at their current scholarship amounts, it would cost Tech $668,000.
All 2020 spring sport athletes, such as the Virginia Tech softball team, have been granted another year of eligibility. Tech athletic director Whit Babcock said if all Tech's current spring-sports seniors returned with their current amount of scholarship money, it would cost Tech $668,000.
The Virginia Tech athletic department is not implementing pay cuts, but that doesnat mean coaches and administrators wonat be asked to open up their wallets.
The cancellation of the NCAA menas basketball tournament because of the coronavirus pandemic will affect all NCAA schools. The NCAA was planning to give Division I schools $600 million in the coming months, but that sum will drop to $225 million because of the cancellation of the NCAA winter and spring sports championships.
Virginia Tech athletic director Whit Babcock figures Tech and other ACC schools will each be getting $2 million to $2.3 million less from the NCAA in the coming months.
aThat will hit us this fiscal year,a Babcock said Wednesday on a teleconference. aThe ACC is certainly looking at insurance; theyare looking at creative ways to spend some reserve money to try to keep us whole as possible.a
Tech is looking at ways to stay whole, too.
At Iowa State, all coaches and athletic department employees have already been hit with a 10% pay cut because of the looming drop in NCAA revenue.
Babcock said aVT is not there yeta when it comes to pay cuts. He will follow the lead of Tech President Timothy Sands and the university on that matter.
aItas important to Dr. Sands and our administration to try and keep everyone whole through this health crisis and economic crisis, and especially the rank-and-file,a Babcock said.
aI also understand the verse, aTo those who have been given much, much is expected,a right? I also believe that personal giving to the Hokie Club from our senior administration and head coaches is a wonderful way to give back and put skin in the game.
aI donat believe you will see personal giving numbers publicized from me, [football] Coach [Justin] Fuente and [menas basketball] Coach [Mike] Young, but you can rest assured those conversations are happening. And we know that weare in a position to sacrifice for the good of the cause.a
Babcock said there are other ways to take a pay cut that donat affect base salaries.
aWeare developing a plan within our department. Iad rather our folks hear it from me,a he said. aYou can look at things like supplemental pay, stipends, bonuses.
aI donat think youall see us up there beating our chest about what weave done, but make no mistake about it, that will be done.a
Fuente was asked about the possibility of a pay cut on a separate teleconference Wednesday.
aThereas a lot of topics at play,a he said. aWeave discussed a lot of them and I think thereas a lot more on the horizon for us to discuss as we a| get a better handle on the effects of whatas happening. Thereas a lot of contingency plans for all of those things that weare working out. In my opinion, itas a little too earlya| for us to say with any certainty how itas all going to work out.a
Babcock might also turn to his employees to help with an unexpected need for more scholarship money.
Last week, the NCAA Division I Council granted 2020 spring-sports athletes another year of eligibility. But the council gave schools the freedom to offer current seniors less scholarship money next year a or none at all.
Tech is still in the process of finding out which seniors want to return.
Babcock said if all the current spring-sports seniors returned next year with the same amount of scholarship money, it would cost Tech $668,000.
aBut we donat have $668,000 laying around,a Babcock said. aBut we do have an internal plan for people in our department to put skin in the game to help this cause.a
Babcock was asked after the teleconference if askin in the gamea means coaches and athletic department employees will be donating money to help pay for those scholarships. But he would not be more specific. He said in a direct message on Twitter that there are several options but he has not yet spelled them out to people in the department.
Some schools do not have extra money for current seniors who want to return.
The athletic scholarship budgets at Radford and VMI will not be expanded next year. Coaches at those schools will have to try to find money for seniors who want to return out of the 2020-21 scholarship funds that teams have already been assigned.
aThereas some schools and conferences and probably some schools in the ACC that will just say, aYou know what, weare going to do zero [extra dollars], and head coaches have to fit it under their current scholarship numbers and amounts,a a Babcock said on the teleconference.
aAnd then there will be schools on the other end of the spectrum that will say, aWe have enough reserve, we have enough revenue, we will fund it to the nth-degree.
aAnd we are shooting in the middle, so to speak, trying to figure out what we really need to do, whatas right by the student-athlete, whatas right budget-wise, PR-wise. And we feel like weave about got to plan a navigate that. But there will be some skin in the game.a
Because of the uncertainty about how long college campuses will be closed because of the pandemic, some athletic directors fear a sharp decline in revenue for the 2020-21 school year. In a recent survey of more than 100 FBS athletic directors, 63% said they expect revenue to drop by at least 20% in the 2020-21 school year.
Babcock, who did not participate in that survey, said he does not doubt that revenue will be down. But he isnat sure how big the drop might be.
aItas way too premature to start throwing out numbers like 20%, 30%,a he said. aYouave got football season. Youave got insurance. Youave got reserves. Youave got lines of credit.
aWe will be working with the campus folks and all our financials and 10-year planning. a| We feel like weall be OK.a
Mike Niziolek contributed to this report.
Mark Berman covers Virginia Tech menas basketball and many other teams at the university. He also helps cover other colleges, including Radford, VMI, Roanoke, Washington and Lee and Ferrum.
